window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>1","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"MACHINES :","question":"The diagram below illustrates a pulley system used to raise a 10\u2009kg load. If the effort F needed to raise the load is 70\u2009N, calculate the efficiency of the machine. [g = 10\u2009ms\u22122]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"20.0%","B":"35.7%","C":"50.0%","D":"75.0%"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Load (L) = 10 kg; Effort (E) = 70 N; g = 10\u2009ms\u22122; \u03b5 = ?    Load, L, in Newtons = 10 \u00d7 10 = 100 N    Since the number of pulleys is 4    \u2234 V.R = 4    \u03b5=M.AV.R\u00d7100%=L/EV.R\u00d7100%  \u03b5=100/704\u00d7100%=10070 \u00d7 4\u00d7100%  \u03b5=100280\u00d7100%  \u03b5 = 0.357 \u00d7 100%    \u2234 \u03b5 = 35.7%","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>2","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"WORK, ENERGY AND POWER : CONCEPT OF WORK","question":"The diagram below illustrates the force-displacement graph of a body. Calculate the work done during the first 20\u2009m of motion.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"1000\u2009J","B":"825\u2009J","C":"750\u2009J","D":"500\u2009J"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The work done during the first 20\u2009m of motion is the area of the shape ABCDE.    Adding up the areas of each shape in ABCDE would give the working done during the first 20\u2009m of motion.    Work done = I + II + III + IV     Work done = (15 \u00d7 10) + (15 \u00d7 10) + (1/2 \u00d7 10 \u00d7 (50 \u2212 15)) + (50 \u2212 15) \u00d7 10    Work done = 150 + 150 + 1/2 \u00d7 10 \u00d7 35 + 35 \u00d7 10    \u2234 Work done = 150 + 150 + 175 + 350 = 825 J","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>3","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : DISPERSION OF WHITE LIGHT","question":"The dispersion of light would result in which of the following phenomena?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Eclipse","B":"Shadow","C":"Rainbow","D":"Mirage"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The dispersion of light is the phenomenon where light is separated into its different colors (wavelengths) as it passes through a medium, such as a prism or water droplets. This happens because different colors of light bend (refract) by different amounts when passing through a medium.    A rainbow is formed when sunlight is dispersed by water droplets in the atmosphere, splitting the light into its constituent colors (red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo, and violet).","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>4","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : HEAT TRANSFER","question":"The best color of shirt to be worn on a bright noon day is","images":[],"options":{"A":"red.","B":"black.","C":"green.","D":"white."},"answer":"D","explanation":"On a hot, sunny day, the best clothing color is one that reflects sunlight rather than absorbing it.    White reflects most of the sunlight, keeping you cooler.    Black absorbs all wavelengths of light, converting them into heat, making you feel hotter.    Red, Green, and other dark colors also absorb more light than white, though not as much as black.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>5","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"The image formed when an object is placed between the focus and centre of a converging lens is","images":[],"options":{"A":"real, inverted and magnified.","B":"real, inverted and diminished.","C":"erect, virtual and magnified.","D":"erect, virtual and diminished."},"answer":"A","explanation":"For a converging lens (convex lens), when an object is placed between the focus (F) and the center of curvature (2F), the image formed is:    Real (can be projected on a screen),    Inverted,    Magnified (larger than the object),    And formed beyond 2F on the opposite side of the lens.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>6","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CONCEPTS OF ELECTRIC FIELD, ELECTRIC FIELD INTENSITY (POTENTIAL GRADIENT) AND ELECTRIC POTENTIAL.~~MAGNETIC FIELD : MAGNETIC FORCE ON A MOVING CHARGED PARTICLE","question":"For a charged body moving in an electric and magnetic crossed field, the ratio of the electric field intensity, E to the magnetic flux density, B is known as","images":[],"options":{"A":"Lorentz ratio.","B":"Charge ratio.","C":"Velocity selector.","D":"Electrochemical equivalence."},"answer":"C","explanation":"When a charged particle moves through crossed electric (E) and magnetic (B) fields, it experiences forces due to both fields. In a velocity selector, the fields are adjusted such that only particles with a specific velocity v = E/B pass through undeflected. This setup is used in devices like mass spectrometers.    F = qvB = qE    vB = E    \u2234v=EB","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>7","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"SOUND WAVES : CHARACTERISTICS OF SOUND","question":"A note, K from a keyboard has an amplitude of 0.5\u2009cm and frequency 2000\u2009Hz. Another note, M from a guitar has an amplitude of 1.5\u2009cm and frequency 2000\u2009Hz. Which of the following statements is true if the two notes are compared?","images":[],"options":{"A":"K is louder than M","B":"M is louder than K","C":"M has a higher pitch than K","D":"K and M have the same timbre."},"answer":"B","explanation":"Loudness of a sound is related to its amplitude \u2014 the greater the amplitude, the louder the sound.    Note K has amplitude 0.5 cm    Note M has amplitude 1.5 cm (which is greater)  Both have the same frequency (2000 Hz), so they have the same pitch, not loudness.  Therefore, M is louder than K.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>8","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : PERIOD, FREQUENCY AND AMPLITUDE OF A BODY EXECUTING S.H.M","question":"A simple pendulum of length 0.8\u2009m is set oscillating on a planet. If the pendulum completes 20 oscillations in 60\u2009s, calculate the acceleration due to gravity on this planet. [\u03c0 = 3.14]","images":[],"options":{"A":"2.5\u2009ms\u22122","B":"3.0\u2009ms\u22122","C":"3.5\u2009ms\u22122","D":"3.8\u2009ms\u22122"},"answer":"C","explanation":"L = 0.8 m; n = 20; t = 60 s; \u03c0 = 3.14; g = ?    T=tn=6020=3  To calculate the acceleration due to gravity (g) on the planet, we'll use the formula for the period of a simple pendulum:    T=2\u03c0&radic;Lg&nbsp;  3=2(3.14)\u00d7&radic;0.8g&nbsp;  3=6.28\u00d7&radic;0.8g&nbsp;  36.28=&radic;0.8g&nbsp;  (36.28)2=0.8g  g=0.8\u00f7(36.28)2  g = 3.506\u2009ms\u22122    \u2234 g \u2243 3.5\u2009ms\u22122","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>9","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : SPECIFIC HEAT CAPACITY","question":"A liquid of mass 2\u2009kg at 61\u00b0C is kept in a lagged vessel. If another 2\u2009kg of the same liquid at 21\u00b0C is added to the liquid in the vessel, calculate the final temperature of the mixture.","images":[],"options":{"A":"50\u00b0C","B":"41\u00b0C","C":"30\u00b0C","D":"15\u00b0C"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Mass of hot liquid (m\u2081) = 2 kg    Mass of cold liquid (m\u2082) = 2 kg    Temperature of hot liquid (\u03b8\u2081) = 61\u00b0C    Temperature of cold liquid (\u03b8\u2082) = 21\u00b0C    Specific heat capacity (c) is same for both liquids (since they are the same substance)    Heat Lost by Hot Liquid = Heat Gained by Cold Liquid    The hot liquid cools down, and the cold liquid warms up until they reach the same final temperature (\u03b8f).    m\u2081c(\u03b8\u2081 \u2212 \u03b8f) = m\u2082c(\u03b8f \u2212 \u03b8\u2082)    \u21d2 m\u2081(\u03b8\u2081 \u2212 \u03b8f) = m\u2082(\u03b8f \u2212 \u03b8\u2082)    Since m\u2081 and m\u2082 are equal    \u21d2 \u03b8\u2081 \u2212 \u03b8f = \u03b8f \u2212 \u03b8\u2082    \u21d2 61\u00b0C \u2212 \u03b8f = \u03b8f \u2212 21\u00b0C    \u21d2 61\u00b0C + 21\u00b0C = \u03b8f + \u03b8f    \u21d2 82\u00b0C = 2\u03b8f    \u2234\u03b8f=82\u00b0C2=41\u00b0C","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>10","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTROMAGNETIC FIELD : LENZ\u2019S LAW","question":"The diagrams below indicate the current induced in a coil as a result of relative motion between it and a bar magnet. Which of the diagrams illustrates the direction of the induced current?","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"","B":"","C":"","D":""},"answer":"D","explanation":"Case 1: North pole moved towards the loop  The approaching north pole increases the magnetic flux into the loop.    The loop opposes this increase by creating its own north pole (to repel the approaching magnet).    To create a north pole facing the magnet, the current must flow in the counterclockwise direction (when viewed from the magnet's side).      Case 2: North pole moved away from the loop  The magnetic flux decreases as the north pole recedes.    The loop tries to maintain the flux by attracting the magnet \u2014 i.e., creating a south pole facing the receding north pole.    To create a south pole, current must flow in the clockwise direction (again, viewed from the magnet's side).","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>11","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : HEAT TRANSFER","question":"If two bodies, A and B are each in thermal equilibrium with another body C, then the three bodies are in thermal equilibrium with each other. This is the statement of","images":[],"options":{"A":"Zeroth law of thermodynamics.","B":"First law of thermodynamics.","C":"Second law of thermodynamics.","D":"Third law of thermodynamics."},"answer":"A","explanation":"The Zeroth law of thermodynamics states that:    If two bodies (A and B) are each in thermal equilibrium with a third body (C), then A and B are in thermal equilibrium with each other.    This law forms the basis for the concept of temperature.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>12","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"SIMPLE A.C. CIRCUITS : PEAK AND R..M.S. VALUES","question":"A constant voltage source in the circuit below supplies a sinusoidal alternating e.m.f., the voltages marked against the components are the peak values.    Determine the peak value of the applied e.m.f.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"11.0\u2009V","B":"9.0\u2009V","C":"8.0\u2009V","D":"5.0\u2009V"},"answer":"D","explanation":"VR = 3 V; VL = 6 V; VC = 2 V    Vo = &radic;VR2 + (VL \u2212 VC)2&nbsp;    Vo = &radic;32 + (6 \u2212 2)2&nbsp;    Vo = &radic;32 + 42&nbsp;    Vo = &radic;9 + 16&nbsp;    Vo = &radic;25&nbsp;    \u2234 Vo = 5.0 V","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>13","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"SOUND WAVES : TRANSMISSION OF SOUND WAVES","question":"A vibrator is used to generate ripples in a ripple tank. If the distance between two successive troughs is 3.5\u2009cm and the wave travels a distance of 31.5\u2009cm in 1.5\u2009s, calculate the frequency of the vibrator.","images":[],"options":{"A":"3.0\u2009Hz","B":"6.0\u2009Hz","C":"9.0\u2009Hz","D":"12.0\u2009Hz"},"answer":"B","explanation":"\u03bb = 3.5 cm; x = 31.5 cm; t = 1.5 s    v=xt=31.51.5=21cms-1  v=f\u03bb\u21d2f=v\u03bb  \u2234f=213.5=6.0Hz","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>14","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"The speed of light in medium A of refractive index 1.5 is 2.0 \u00d7 108\u2009ms\u22121. Determine the speed of light in medium B of refractive index 1.2.","images":[],"options":{"A":"1.8 \u00d7 108\u2009ms\u22121","B":"2.5 \u00d7 108\u2009ms\u22121","C":"2.7 \u00d7 108\u2009ms\u22121","D":"3.0 \u00d7 108\u2009ms\u22121"},"answer":"B","explanation":"nA = 1.5; vA = 2.0 \u00d7 108; nB = 1.2, vB = ?    nAnB=vBvA\u21d2vB=nAnB\u00d7vA  vB=1.51.2\u00d72.0\u00d7108  vB = 1.25 \u00d7 2.0 \u00d7 108    \u2234 vB = 2.5 \u00d7 108","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>15","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"SOUND WAVES : SPEED OF SOUND","question":"The wavelength of a sound note travelling with a speed of 360\u2009ms\u22121 is 600\u2009m. Determine the period of the note.","images":[],"options":{"A":"60.000\u2009s","B":"6.000\u2009s","C":"1.667\u2009s","D":"0.167\u2009s"},"answer":"C","explanation":"v = 360\u2009ms\u22121; \u03bb = 600 m; T = ?    v=f\u03bb\u21d2f=v\u03bb  f=360600=0.6Hz  ButT=1f  \u2234T=10.6=1.667s","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>16","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"MACHINES :","question":"In which of the following levers is the effort applied between the load and the fulcrum?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Pliers","B":"Wheelbarrow","C":"Sugar tongs","D":"Table knife"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In Class 3 Levers (a.k.a Third Order Levers), the effort is applied between the load and the fulcrum. This arrangement is seen in:    Sugar tongs: The effort (squeezing force) is applied between the fulcrum (pivot point) and the load (sugar being gripped).    Other examples: Tweezers, human arm, fishing rod.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>17","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"Use the circuit diagram below to answer question 17 and 18.      The current passing through the 6\u2009\u03a9 resistor is 1.5\u2009A. Calculate the current in the 3\u2009\u03a9 resistor.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"1.20\u2009A","B":"0.90\u2009A","C":"0.75\u2009A","D":"0.60\u2009A"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Using the current divider rule,    I3\u03a9=R2\u03a9R3\u03a9 + R2\u03a9\u00d7I  I3\u03a9=23 + 2\u00d71.5  I3\u03a9=25\u00d71.5  \u2234 I3\u03a9 = 0.60 A","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>18","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"Use the circuit diagram below to answer question 17 and 18.    Calculate the terminal p.d of the battery in the diagram.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"7.20\u2009V","B":"7.30\u2009V","C":"10.80\u2009V","D":"11.25\u2009V"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Terminal p.d, V = IRT    RT=3 \u00d7 23 + 2+6=65+6  RT = 1.2 + 6 = 7.2 \u03a9    \u2234 V = 1.5 \u00d7 7.2 = 10.80 V","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>19","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : COMPOSITION OF THE NUCLEUS","question":"Which of the statements is correct about the nucleus of an atom? It  I. is centrally located in the atom.  II. contains the nucleons and electrons.  III. is positively charged due to the protons.  IV. decays when there is instability inside.","images":[],"options":{"A":"I, II and IV only","B":"I, III, and IV only","C":"I, II, and III only","D":"I and II only"},"answer":"B","explanation":"I. \"The nucleus is centrally located in the atom.\"    True. The nucleus sits at the center of the atom, surrounded by electrons in orbitals.    II. \"The nucleus contains the nucleons and electrons.\"    False. The nucleus contains protons and neutrons (nucleons) but not electrons, which reside outside the nucleus in electron shells.    III. \"The nucleus is positively charged due to the protons.\"    True. Protons carry a positive charge, while neutrons are neutral. The net charge of the nucleus is positive.    IV. \"The nucleus decays when there is instability inside.\"    True. Nuclear decay (e.g., alpha/beta decay) occurs when the nucleus is unstable (e.g., due to an excess of protons/neutrons).","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>20","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : RADIOACTIVITY","question":"A radioactive element of mass 16\u2009g was isolated and stored. It was discovered that after 40\u2009days only 1\u2009g of the element remained undecayed. Calculate the half-life of the element.","images":[],"options":{"A":"2.5\u2009days","B":"5.0\u2009days","C":"10.0\u2009days","D":"15.0\u2009days"},"answer":"C","explanation":"No = 16 g; N = 1 g; t = 40 days, T1/2 = ?    The fraction of the substance remaining is given by:    NNo=(12)n  \u21d2116=(12)n  \u21d2124=(12)n  \u21d2(12)4=(12)n  \u21d2n=4(numberofhalf-lives)  T1/2=tn=404  \u2234T1/2=10.0days","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>21","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"SOUND WAVES : ECHOES AND REVERBERATION","question":"Which of the following reasons explains why the walls and ceilings of a standard concert hall are usually covered with perforated pads? To","images":[],"options":{"A":"increase the intensity of sound waves.","B":"increase the loudness of sound waves.","C":"reduce the effect of reverberation of sound waves.","D":"decrease the frequency of sound waves."},"answer":"C","explanation":"In a concert hall, perforated pads or acoustic panels are used to absorb sound waves and prevent excessive reflections from the walls and ceilings. This helps to:    - Minimize reverberation (prolonged echoing of sound),    - Improve clarity and quality of the sound,    - Ensure that sound does not become muddled or distorted.    - They do not increase intensity, loudness, or alter the frequency of sound.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>22","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION (S.H.M)","question":"A bucket of water of mass 10\u2009kg is swung in a vertical circle of radius 1.2\u2009m. While at the lowest position of the swing, its speed is 5\u2009ms\u22121. Determine the tension in the string. (g = 10\u2009ms\u22122)","images":[],"options":{"A":"41.7\u2009N","B":"141.7\u2009N","C":"208.3\u2009N","D":"308.3\u2009N"},"answer":"D","explanation":"m = 10kg; r = 1.2m; v = 5 ms\u22121; g = 10 ms\u22122; T = ?    At the lowest position, the net force towards the center is T \u2212 mg.    T\u2212mg=mv2r  T=mv2r+mg  T=10 \u00d7 521.2+10\u00d710  T=10 \u00d7 251.2+10\u00d710  T=2501.2+100  T = 208.3 + 100    \u2234 T = 308.3 N","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>23","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : APPLICATION OF LENSES IN OPTICAL INSTRUMENTS","question":"A man's near point is 30\u2009cm. Which of the following eye defects is the man likely to suffer from?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Hypermetropia","B":"Myopia","C":"Presbyopia","D":"Astigmatism"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The near point is the closest distance at which the eye can focus on an object clearly.  For a normal eye, the near point is about 25 cm.    If a man's near point is 30 cm, it means he cannot see nearby objects clearly \u2014 his eye cannot focus properly on objects that are close.    This condition is known as:    Hypermetropia (farsightedness) \u2014 the eye can see distant objects clearly but struggles with nearby ones.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>24","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : DISPERSION OF WHITE LIGHT","question":"White light can be produced by a combination of  I. magenta, yellow and cyan.  II. red, blue and green.  III. magenta and green.  IV. yellow, red and green.","images":[],"options":{"A":"II only","B":"I, II and III only","C":"I and IV only","D":"II and III only"},"answer":"B","explanation":"I. Magenta, Yellow, and Cyan  These are the secondary colors of light.    When combined additively, they reproduce all primary colors (Red, Green, Blue), which combine to give white light.    II. Red, Blue, and Green  These are the primary colors of light.    Their additive combination = white light.    III. Magenta and Green  Magenta = Red + Blue    Magenta + Green = Red + Blue + Green = White    IV. Yellow, Red and Green  Yellow = Red + Green    So Yellow + Red + Green = Mostly Red and Green components \u2192 not full-spectrum \u2192 not white    Therefore, white light can be produced by a combination of I, II and III.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>25","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFLECTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"The diagram below shows a beam of light incident on a mirror. Such a mirror can be used as","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"surveillance mirror.","B":"make-up mirror.","C":"reflector in microscope.","D":"depressing mirror."},"answer":"A","explanation":"The diagram shows a beam of light incident on a mirror (diverging mirror). A diverging mirror is also known as a convex mirror.    Convex mirrors have the following properties:    - They always form virtual, erect, and diminished (smaller) images.  - They have a wide field of view because they cause parallel rays to diverge and reflections spread out.    Let's analyze the options based on these properties:    Surveillance mirror: Convex mirrors are commonly used as surveillance mirrors (e.g., in shops, on roads at blind corners) because their wide field of view allows them to cover a large area, even though the objects appear smaller. This fits the properties of a diverging mirror.    Make-up mirror: Make-up mirrors are typically concave mirrors (converging mirrors). They are used to produce a magnified, erect (virtual) image when the face is placed within the focal length, which helps in applying make-up. A diverging mirror would make the face look smaller.    Reflector in a microscope: Microscopes primarily use lenses (refracting light) to magnify objects. While some illumination systems might use mirrors, the primary magnification in a microscope comes from converging lenses. A diverging mirror would not be suitable for producing magnified images for observation.    Depressing mirror: This is not a standard term for a type of mirror or its function in optics.    Therefore, a diverging mirror (convex mirror) is best used as a surveillance mirror.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>26","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"PROPERTIES OF WAVES : SUPERPOSITION","question":"Which of the following statements about stationary wave is not true?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Particles between adjacent nodes vibrate out of phase with each other.","B":"Successive nodes or antinodes occur at intervals of half a wavelength.","C":"Particles between adjacent nodes vibrate in phase with each other.","D":"Particles between adjacent nodes have different amplitudes."},"answer":"A","explanation":"A. Particles between adjacent nodes vibrate out of phase with each other.  This statement is NOT TRUE. In a stationary wave, all particles between any two successive nodes vibrate in phase with each other. Their displacements reach maximums and minimums at the same time, though their amplitudes vary. Particles on opposite sides of a node vibrate out of phase with each other.     B. Successive nodes or antinodes occur at intervals of half a wavelength.  This statement is TRUE.    The distance between two consecutive nodes is \u03bb/2.  The distance between two consecutive antinodes is \u03bb/2.  The distance between a node and an adjacent antinode is \u03bb/4.     C. Particles between adjacent nodes vibrate in phase with each other.  This statement is TRUE. As explained in A, all particles in a single segment (between two nodes) oscillate synchronously.    D. Particles between adjacent nodes have different amplitudes.  This statement is TRUE. At the nodes, the amplitude of vibration is zero. At the antinodes (midway between nodes), the amplitude is maximum. For all other points between a node and an antinode, the amplitude varies, increasing from zero at the node to a maximum at the antinode, and then decreasing back to zero at the next node.    Therefore, the statement that is not true is:  A. Particles between adjacent nodes vibrate out of phase with each other.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>27","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"SOUND WAVES : VIBRATION OF AIR IN PIPE \u2013 OPEN AND CLOSED PIPES","question":"In a pipe closed at one end and open at the other end, the overtones that accompany the fundamental frequency are","images":[],"options":{"A":"odd integer multiples of the fundamental frequency.","B":"even integer multiples of the fundamental frequency.","C":"all integer multiples of the fundamental frequency.","D":"prime integer multiples of the fundamental frequency."},"answer":"A","explanation":"For a pipe closed at one end and open at the other (a closed pipe system):    The fundamental mode (first harmonic) has a node at the closed end and an antinode at the open end.    Only odd harmonics are produced because the pipe can only accommodate odd-numbered quarter wavelengths.    The overtones produced are the 3rd, 5th, 7th, and so on, harmonics. These are odd integer multiples of the fundamental frequency. Even harmonics are not present in a pipe closed at one end and open at the other.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>28","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : RADIOACTIVITY","question":"A radioactive substance of mass 512.0\u2009g decays to 64.0\u2009g. Determine the number of half-lives involved in the decay.","images":[],"options":{"A":"8","B":"6","C":"4","D":"3"},"answer":"D","explanation":"No = 512.0 g, N = 64.0 g, n = ?    After each half-life, the mass halves:    1. After 1st half-life:\u00a0512 \u00f7 2 = 256 g    2. After 2nd half-life:\u00a0256 \u00f7 2 = 128 g    3. After 3rd half-life:\u00a0128 \u00f7 2 = 64 g    \u2234 The number of half-lives involved in the decay is 3.    ALTERNATIVELY    The remaining mass after n half-lives is given by:    NNo=(12)n  64512=(12)n  18=(12)n  123=(12)n  (12)3=(12)n  \u2234 n = 3    This confirms that 3 half-lives have passed.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>29","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"PROPERTIES OF WAVES : INTERFERENCE","question":"Two waves will interfere destructively if the path difference between the waves is","images":[],"options":{"A":"one wavelength.","B":"one-half wavelength.","C":"one-quarter wavelength.","D":"one-eighth wavelength."},"answer":"B","explanation":"Destructive interference occurs when two waves meet out of phase - meaning the crest of one aligns with the trough of the other, causing cancellation.  This happens when the path difference between the two waves is an odd multiple of half a wavelength:  Path difference = (n + 1/2)\u03bb, where n = 0, 1, 2, ...     The simplest case is when path difference = 1/2\u03bb (i.e., half a wavelength).","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>30","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTROMAGNETIC FIELD : INDUCTANCE","question":"Which of the following statements about a step-up transformer is correct? It has","images":[],"options":{"A":"less number of turns in the primary coil than in the secondary coil.","B":"more number of turns in the primary coil than in the secondary coil.","C":"equal number of turns in the primary coil and the secondary coil.","D":"its primary coil far away from the secondary coil."},"answer":"A","explanation":"A step-up transformer is designed to increase voltage from the primary coil to the secondary coil. This is achieved by having:    - Fewer turns in the primary coil (Np)  - More turns in the secondary coil (Ns)","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>31","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTROMAGNETIC FIELD : FARADAY\u2019S LAW","question":"The unit of magnetic flux density is","images":[],"options":{"A":"Tesla.","B":"Watt.","C":"Newton per metre.","D":"Coulomb."},"answer":"A","explanation":"The Tesla is the SI unit of magnetic flux density (also known as magnetic field strength or B-field). One Tesla is defined as one Weber per square meter (1\u00a0T = 1\u00a0Wb/m2). It's named after Nikola Tesla","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>32","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"Meters are installed in houses to monitor and evaluate the cost of the electricity consumed. What physical quantity does this meter measure?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Power","B":"Energy","C":"Voltage","D":"Current"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Meters installed in houses (often called electricity meters or kilowatt-hour meters) monitor and evaluate the cost of electricity consumed by measuring Energy.    Electricity bills are based on the amount of electrical energy consumed, which is usually measured in kilowatt-hours (kWh).    Power (measured in Watts or kilowatts) is the rate at which energy is used.  Energy (measured in Joules or kilowatt-hours) is the total amount of work done or heat produced over a period of time.  The meter continuously measures the instantaneous power (voltage multiplied by current) and integrates it over time to give the total energy consumed.    Therefore, the physical quantity measured by these meters is Energy.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>33","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : PRODUCTION OF ELECTRIC CURRENT","question":"The type of energy stored by a dry Leclanch\u00e9 cell is","images":[],"options":{"A":"chemical.","B":"electrical.","C":"nuclear.","D":"thermal."},"answer":"A","explanation":"A dry Leclanch\u00e9 cell (a common type of dry cell battery) stores chemical energy, which is converted into electrical energy when the cell is in use.    The cell contains chemical substances (like zinc and manganese dioxide) that undergo redox reactions.    This reaction produces a flow of electrons, i.e., electric current.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>34","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF ENERGY","question":"The microphone transforms energy from","images":[],"options":{"A":"electrical to sound.","B":"sound to electrical.","C":"electrical to mechanical.","D":"sound to mechanical."},"answer":"B","explanation":"A microphone is a device that converts sound energy into electrical energy.    When you speak into a microphone, sound waves (mechanical vibrations in air) strike a diaphragm inside the mic.    These vibrations are converted into electrical signals that can be amplified, recorded, or transmitted.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>35","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : RADIOACTIVITY","question":"A hospital received 16\u2009g of a radioactive substance at 1300 hour GMT. At 1700 hour GMT, the fraction of the substance left unchanged was 1/16\u200b. Determine the half-life of the substance.","images":[],"options":{"A":"4 hours","B":"2 hours","C":"1 hour","D":"0.5 hour"},"answer":"C","explanation":"No=16g;NNo=116  Timeelapsed=1700-1300=4hours  T1/2=?  Usingthedecayformula:  NNo=(12)n  116=(12)n  124=(12)n  (12)4=(12)n  n=4(numberofhalf-lives)  T1/2=Time elapsedn=44  \u2234T1/2=1hour","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>36","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"NEWTON\u2019S LAWS OF MOTION : THIRD LAW","question":"Which of the following situations pertains to Newton's third law of motion?","images":[],"options":{"A":"A ball rolling on the ground","B":"An accelerating car","C":"A rocket propelled into space","D":"Pedalling of bicycle"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Newton's Third Law of Motion states:    For every action, there is an equal and opposite reaction.    In a rocket launch, hot gases are expelled downward (action), and the rocket is pushed upward (reaction).    This is a classic example of Newton's third law in action.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>37","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"WORK, ENERGY AND POWER : CONCEPT OF POWER","question":"The force and velocity of a system are each reduced simultaneously by one-half. The power of the system is","images":[],"options":{"A":"doubled.","B":"reduced by a quarter.","C":"reduced by half.","D":"constant."},"answer":"B","explanation":"Given:    Initial Force (F\u2081): F    Initial Velocity (v\u2081): v    Initial Power (P\u2081): P = F \u00d7 v    After reduction:    NewForce(F\u2082):F2\u200b  NewVelocity(v\u2082):v2\u200b  NewPower(P\u2082):F\u2082\u00d7v\u2082=F2\u00d7v2=F \u00d7 v4=P4\u200b  Therefore, the power is reduced to one-quarter of its original value.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>38","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"MACHINES :","question":"A plane is inclined at 45\u00b0 to the horizontal. Calculate the velocity ratio of the plane.","images":[],"options":{"A":"0.71","B":"1.00","C":"1.41","D":"1.71"},"answer":"C","explanation":"\u03b8 = 45\u00b0; V.R = ?    V.R=1sin\u03b8=1sin45\u00b0  \u2234 V.R = 1.41","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>39","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"GRAVITATIONAL FIELD : ACCELERATION DUE TO GRAVITY","question":"A body in a lift is moving down with acceleration due to gravity. Which of the following statements is correct? The body","images":[],"options":{"A":"weighs less than its actual weight.","B":"weighs more than its actual weight.","C":"weighs exactly its own weight.","D":"is weightless."},"answer":"D","explanation":"When a lift (elevator) is moving downward with acceleration equal to gravity (a = g), it is in free fall.  In this condition, the apparent weight of the body becomes:  Wapparent = m(g \u2212 a)   Since a = g, then:  Wapparent = m(g \u2212 g) = 0   This means the person or object experiences weightlessness - there is no contact force acting on them from the floor.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>40","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"FLUID AT REST : VISCOSITY (FRICTION IN FLUIDS)","question":"When the pressure in oil is increased, the viscosity of the oil would be","images":[],"options":{"A":"increased.","B":"decreased.","C":"constant.","D":"increased, then decreased."},"answer":"A","explanation":"Viscosity is the resistance of a fluid to flow.    For liquids like oil:    When pressure increases, the molecules are pushed closer together, reducing their ability to move past one another.    This causes an increase in internal friction, and hence, an increase in viscosity.    NB: This behavior is opposite to gases, where increasing pressure can reduce viscosity under certain conditions.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>41","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : COMPOSITION OF THE NUCLEUS","question":"What is the number of neutrons in 146C?","images":[],"options":{"A":"6","B":"8","C":"14","D":"20"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Mass number (A) = 14  Atomic number (Z) = 6 (which is the number of protons)  Number of neutrons = A - Z = 14 - 6 = 8","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>42","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : TEMPERATURE AND ITS MEASUREMENT","question":"The ice and steam points of a resistance thermometer are 12.0\u2009\u03a9 and 20.0\u2009\u03a9 respectively. Calculate the resistance of the thermometer at 10\u00b0C.","images":[],"options":{"A":"12.4\u2009\u03a9","B":"12.8\u2009\u03a9","C":"13.2\u2009\u03a9","D":"13.4\u2009\u03a9"},"answer":"B","explanation":"We are given:    Ice point (0\u00b0C) resistance: R0 = 12.0\u2009\u03a9    Steam point (100\u00b0C) resistance: R100 = 20.0\u2009\u03a9    Temperature: \u03b8 = 10\u00b0C    Find: Resistance at 10\u00b0C (R\u03b8)    \u03b8 \u2212 0100 \u2212 0=R\u03b8 \u2212 R0R100 \u2212 R0  10 \u2212 0100 \u2212 0=R\u03b8 \u2212 1220 \u2212 12  10100=R\u03b8 \u2212 128  100(R\u03b8 \u2212 12) = 80    100R\u03b8 \u2212 1200 = 80    100R\u03b8 = 80 + 1200    100R\u03b8 = 1280    \u2234R\u03b8=1280100=12.8\u03a9","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>43","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : FUSION AND FISSION","question":"A radium nuclide decays by emitting an alpha particle as shown below.  22688Ra \u2192 X + 42He. Determine the daughter nuclide.","images":[],"options":{"A":"22286X","B":"22288X","C":"23086X","D":"23088X"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Applying Conservation Laws:    1. Conservation of Mass Number (A):     226 = AX + 4    AX \u200b= 226 - 4 = 222    2. Conservation of Atomic Number (Z):     88 = ZX + 2    ZX \u200b= 88 - 2 = 86    The nuclide with Z = 86 is Radon (Rn). Thus:    \u2234 X = 22286Rn","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>44","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : COMPOSITION OF THE NUCLEUS","question":"A bullet of mass 0.025\u2009kg moves at 250\u2009ms\u22121. Calculate its deBroglie wavelength.  [h = 6.67 \u00d7 10\u221234\u2009Js, e = 1.6 \u00d7 10\u221219\u2009C]","images":[],"options":{"A":"6.67 \u00d7 10\u221238\u2009m","B":"5.34 \u00d7 10\u221235\u2009m","C":"1.07 \u00d7 10\u221234\u2009m","D":"2.13 \u00d7 10\u221234\u2009m"},"answer":"C","explanation":"m = 0.025 kg; v = 250\u2009ms\u22121; h = 6.67 \u00d7 10\u221234\u2009Js, e = 1.6 \u00d7 10\u221219\u2009C; \u03bb = ?    \u03bb=hp=hmv  \u03bb=6.67 \u00d7 10\u2212340.025 \u00d7 250  \u2234\u03bb=6.67 \u00d7 10\u2212346.25=1.07\u00d710\u221234","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>45","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"MAGNETIC FIELD : MAGNETIC FORCE ON A MOVING CHARGED PARTICLE","question":"An electron moving with 5.0 \u00d7 105\u2009ms\u22121 enters a magnetic field at 90\u00b0. Calculate the magnitude of the magnetic force on the electron if the magnetic field strength is 0.25\u2009T. [e = 1.6 \u00d7 10\u221219\u2009C]","images":[],"options":{"A":"1.5 \u00d7 10\u221214\u2009N","B":"2.0 \u00d7 10\u221214\u2009N","C":"2.5 \u00d7 10\u221214\u2009N","D":"3.5 \u00d7 10\u221214\u2009N"},"answer":"B","explanation":"v = 5.0 \u00d7 105 ms\u22121; \u03b8 = 90\u00b0; B = 0.25 T; q = 1.6 \u00d7 10\u221219\u2009C; F = ?    To calculate the magnetic force acting on the electron, we'll use the formula for the force on a moving charge in a magnetic field:    F = qvBsin\u03b8    F = 1.6 \u00d7 10\u221219 \u00d7 5.0 \u00d7 105 \u00d7 0.25 \u00d7 sin 90\u00b0    \u2234 F = 2 \u00d7 10\u221214 N","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>46","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : SOURCES OF LIGHT","question":"A beam of light which appears to come from a point in space is said to be","images":[],"options":{"A":"convergent.","B":"divergent.","C":"parallel.","D":"circular."},"answer":"B","explanation":"A beam of light that appears to come from a point in space is called divergent because:    The light rays spread out (diverge) as if originating from a single point.    Examples:    - Light emitted from a point source (like a small bulb).    - Light reflecting off a convex mirror.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>47","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"SOUND WAVES : NOISE AND MUSIC","question":"A sound wave made up of a large number of unrelated frequencies superimposed on each other is called","images":[],"options":{"A":"harmonics.","B":"note.","C":"noise.","D":"pitch."},"answer":"C","explanation":"A sound wave composed of many unrelated (random) frequencies superimposed on each other is known as noise.    Noise lacks a regular pattern or structure, making it non-musical and often unpleasant.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>48","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"MOTION : SOLID FRICTION","question":"A boy pushes a box of mass 80\u2009kg along a horizontal floor with a force of 200\u2009N. If the box is pushed with a uniform velocity, what is the coefficient of friction between the box and the floor?  [g = 10\u2009ms\u22122]","images":[],"options":{"A":"0.25","B":"0.40","C":"0.50","D":"0.65"},"answer":"A","explanation":"m = 80 kg; F = 200 N; g = 10\u2009ms\u22122; \u03bc = ?    Since the box moves at a constant velocity, the net force is zero:    F \u2212 Ffriction = 0    F = Ffriction    F = \u03bcR     F = \u03bcmg (\u2235 R = mg)    \u03bc=Fmg=20080 \u00d7 10  \u2234\u03bc=200800=0.25","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>49","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"HOOKE\u2019S LAW, YOUNG\u2019S MODULES AND WORK DONE IN SPRINGS AND STRING :","question":"Extremely thin wires can be drawn from platinum simply because platinum is","images":[],"options":{"A":"crystalline.","B":"ductile.","C":"hard.","D":"malleable."},"answer":"B","explanation":"Platinum can be drawn into extremely thin wires because it is highly ductile. Here's why:    Ductility is the ability of a material to undergo plastic deformation under tensile stress (i.e., it can be stretched into wires without breaking).    Platinum's Properties:    Its metallic bonds allow layers of atoms to slide past each other when stretched.    It is one of the most ductile metals, alongside gold and silver.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2025>50","subject":"Physics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTROMAGNETIC FIELD : INDUCTANCE","question":"The S.I unit of inductance is","images":[],"options":{"A":"Weber.","B":"Farad.","C":"Henry.","D":"Coulomb."},"answer":"C","explanation":"The SI unit of inductance. Inductance measures a coil's opposition to a change in current, producing an electromotive force (EMF). It's named after Joseph Henry.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"}];